u. \n• Day-ahead prices increased from $23/MWh in fall 2023 to $28/MWh in 2024, an increase of 21%. Real-time prices also increased, from an average of $20/MWh in fall 2023 to nearly $27/MWh in 2024, an increase of 31%. \n• Total day-ahead make-whole payments were up from $20 million in fall 2023 to $26 million in 2024. Outside of January 2024, day-ahead make-whole payments were in the $5 million to $10 million dollar range for the last 18 months, until reaching $13.5 million in November 2024. \n• Total reliability unit commitment make-whole payments were up from $28 million in fall 2023 to $38 million in 2024. Gas resources, particularly simple-cycle resources, accounted for most of the increase. \n\n• Total revenue neutrality uplift for fall 2024 was $58 million, down from $65 million in 2023.\n\n• Average hourly load for the 2024 fall season was 2% above 2023, while the peak hourly load was down 3% compared to 2023.\n\n• Wind generation was the primary technology type in terms of generation during the fall 2024 quarter, accounting for 39% of total generation, a slight increase from 38% in 2023. Coal generation decreased from 26% of total generation in fall 2023 to 25% in 2024. Gas, simple-cycle increased from 10% in fall 2023 to 12% in 2024, while gas, combined-cycle decreased from 16% in fall 2023 to 15% in 2024. \n\n• At the end of November 2024, nameplate wind capacity was 34,556 MW. This is up from 33,325 MW at the end of November 2023, an increase of just over 1,200 MW. The sharp\n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Market highlights Market Monitoring Unit\n\nState of the Market Fall 2024 2 growth in wind capacity has abated somewhat, with just 1,231 MW of new wind generation added to the market in 2024 to date.\n\n• During the fall season, the most congested constraint was located just west of Oklahoma City (CIMXF2CIMXF3 Cimmaron transformer 345/1kV [OKGE] for the loss of three Cimarron transformers (OKGE)]). The top six most congested flowgates for the fall were 