ter storm event relying on different types of capacity ... 72 \n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Market highlights Market Monitoring Unit\n\n#### 1 MARKET HIGHLIGHTS\n\nThis report covers market performance and highlights during the 2024 winter quarter (December 2023 through February 2024). Annual figures shown on the charts in this report represent only this three-month period for each year, unless labelled otherwise. Highlights of this fall period are as follows:\n\n• After peaking around $8/MMBtu in summer 2022, the average gas price at the Panhandle Eastern hub has been in the $2/MMBtu range since February 2023, with the exception of January 2024, which was higher as a result of the winter weather event. Overall, the average gas price was down by 32 percent in winter 2024 in comparison with 2023, with an average price of $2.25/MMBtu in winter 2024 compared to $3.33/MMBtu in 2023. \n• Day-ahead prices decreased from $31/MWh in winter 2023 to $29/MWh in 2024, a decrease of seven percent. Real-time prices also decreased, from an average of $30/MWh in winter 2023 to $24/MWh in 2024, a decrease of 21 percent. This decrease in prices is driven predominantly by the lower gas prices experienced during this period. \n• Total day-ahead make-whole payments were up from $40.2 million in winter 2023 to $41.1 million in 2024. Winter weather events in both December 2022 and January 2024 contributed to the higher level of make-whole payments. Outside of those months, day ahead make-whole payments were in the $5 million to $10 million dollar range for other months in the past two winter seasons. \n• Total reliability unit commitment make-whole payments were down from $52 million in winter 2023 to $31 million in winter 2024. Gas resources, along with ‘other’ resources (primarily fuel oil) accounted for most of the decrease. Much of the decrease can be attributed to a decrease in natural gas prices. \n• Total revenue neutrality uplift for winter 2024 was $13 million, down from $69 mil