e 5-1 Congestion by shadow price, spring ... 47 \nFigure 5-2 Congestion by shadow price, rolling 12 month ... 48 \nFigure 5-3 Congestion by interval, day-ahead ... 49 \nFigure 5-4 Congestion by interval, real-time ... 50 \nFigure 5-5 Total congestion payments ... 50 \nFigure 5-6 Day-ahead, net congestion revenue by market participant, spring ... 51 \nFigure 5-7 Day-ahead and real-time, net congestion revenue by market participant, spring52 \nFigure 5-8 Transmission congestion right funding, month and quarter ... 53 \nFigure 5-9 Transmission congestion right funding, TCR year ... 53 \nFigure 5-10 Transmission congestion right funding, spring ... 54 \nFigure 5-11 Auction revenue right funding, month and quarter ... 55 \n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Market highlights Market Monitoring Unit\n\n#### 1 MARKET HIGHLIGHTS\n\nThis report covers market performance and highlights during the 2025 spring quarter (March – May). Annual figures shown on the charts in this report represent only this three-month period for each year, unless labelled otherwise. Highlights of this spring period are as follows:\n\n• Overall, the average gas price was up by 116% in spring 2025 in comparison with 2024, with an average price of $2.91/MMBtu.\n\n• Day-ahead prices increased from $20.01/MWh in spring 2024 to $30.59/MWh in 2025, an increase of 53%. Real-time prices also increased by the same percentage, increasing from $20.56/MWh in spring 2024 to $31.52/MWh in 2025. This increase in prices is driven predominantly by the increase in gas prices. \n• Total day-ahead make-whole payments were up from $24.0 million in spring 2024 to $25.4 million in 2025. Most of the increase can be attributed to gas, simple-cycle resources. \n• Total reliability unit commitment make-whole payments were up from $24.8 million in spring 2024 to $33.7 million in 2025. Gas resources, particularly simple-cycle resources, accounted for most of the increase. \n\n• Total revenue neutrality uplift for spring 2025 was $104 million, up from $54 million in 2024.\n\n• The average hourly load for the 2025 spring season was 2% above 2024, while the peak hourly load was up 6% compared to 2024.\n\n• Wind generation was the primary technology type in terms of generation during the spring 2025 quarter, accounting for 45% of total generation, a drop from 47% in 2024. Coal generation increased from 19% of total generation in spring 2024 to 22% in 2025. \n\n• At the end of May 2025, nameplate capacity of wind resources was 35,628 MW. This is up from 33,725 MW at the end of May 2024, an increase of 1,903 MW.\n\n• During the spring season, the most congested constraint was located in southeast Kansas (Neosho Ridge Wind-Neosho 345kV [WR] for the loss of Osage-Webber Tap 138kV [CSWS-OKGE]). The rest of the most congested flowgates for the spring were concentrated in Oklahoma (6), with others in southeast Kansas (1), mid-Missouri (1), and eastern Nebraska (1). \n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Market highlights Market Monitoring Unit\n\nState of the Market Spring 2025 2 • Transmission congestion right (TCR) funding for the spring 2025 quarter was 81%, up from 76% in 2024, but down from 90% in 2023. Funding percentages for each month of spring 2025 were 75% for March, 84% for April, and 89% for May.\n\n#### 2 LOAD AND RESOURCES\n\nThis chapter reviews load and resources in the SPP market for the spring 2025 period. Key points from this chapter include:\n\n• The average hourly load for the 2025 spring season was 2% above 2024, while the peak hourly load was up 6% compared to 2024.\n\n• Wind generation was the primary technology type in terms of generation during the spring 2025 quarter, accounting for 45% of total generation, a drop from 47% in 2024. Coal generation increased from 19% of total generation in spring 2024 to 22% in 2025. \n\n• At the end of May 2025, nameplate capacity of wind resources was 35,628 MW. This is up from 33,725 MW at the end of May 2024, an increase of 1,903 MW.\n\n• Net market-to-market payments dropped from $35 million from MISO to SPP in spring 2024 to $22 million in 2025.\n\n• Net virtual profits before fees for spring 2025 averaged $",
